text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages]]%0a%0a!Epenthesis in spoken English by Mandarin speakers%0a%0a:Author: yuluz%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn Mandarin, syllables do not start with complex onset or ending in non-nasal codas, so native mandarin speakers tend to repair the illicit onset and coda components in English with epenthesis.  %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn Mandarin Chinese (Sino-Tibetan),a syllable does not start with a complex onset, neither does it end in any coda except for nasals [n] and [ŋ]. The typical syllable structure in Mandarin would be a simple onset with a nucleus of one or two vowels (CV,CVV) or a simple onset followed by a vowel and a nasal coda (CVC). %0a%0aThis structure causes Mandarin speakers to struggle a bit with pronouncing English syllables that start with complex onsets or end with non-nasal codas. The way they repair it is by inserting vowels between consonants in the complex onset and after the coda. %0a%0aExamples of epenthesis to repair English words with complex onsets include: "fry" as [fuɹaɪ], “play” as [puleɪ], and “glad” as [gəlæd]. Examples of epenthesis to repair the presence of non-nasal coda include: "job" as [ʤɑbu], "check" as [ʧɛkə], “dog” as [dɔgə]. A word in which epenthesis is applied in both onset and coda is “great”, which tend to be pronounced as [guɹeɪtə] by Mandarin speakers. %0a%0aFrom these examples, we can see that the consonant cluster of an obstruent followed by a sonorant seems unnatural to Mandarin speakers and requires the insertion of a vowel to break it up. Furthermore, we can observe that [ə] is added after velar and alveolar plosives, while [u] is added after bilabial plosives /p/ and /b/.%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210512-162020-560470#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-12.05.2021 - 09:20-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210512-162020-560470 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!MarkC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Unique Syllables in Mandarin vs English'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aAdding to the articles point of how syllable onset and coda is more limited in Mandarin than for English, this is evident in the fact that Mandarin has about 1522 unique syllables while English has around 15831.%0a%0aSources:%0a%0ahttps://chinese.stackexchange.com/questions/14596/how-many-syllables-does-chinese-have%0a%0ahttps://web.archive.org/web/20160923005626/http://semarch.linguistics.fas.nyu.edu:80/barker/Syllables/index.txt %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210512-162020-560470#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages:)
